## 2. Lazy Resume — Response handler → `resume()` → `perform()`

With `.lazy` setup (the default), nothing moves until `.resume()` is called. That happens automatically when the first response handler is appended:

```swift
// Request.swift
func appendResponseSerializer(_ closure: @escaping @Sendable () -> Void) {
    mutableState.write { mutableState in
        mutableState.responseSerializers.append(closure)
        // ...
        if mutableState.state.canTransitionTo(.resumed) {
            underlyingQueue.async { [self] in
                if (shouldAutomaticallyResume ?? delegate?.startImmediately) == true {
                    resume()
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

`resume()` transitions the state machine to `.resumed` and, if no `URLSessionTask` exists yet, calls back into the Session:

```swift
public func resume() -> Self {
    let needsToPerform = mutableState.write { mutableState in
        guard mutableState.state.canTransitionTo(.resumed) else { return false }
        mutableState.state = .resumed
        guard let task = mutableState.tasks.last else { return true } // no task yet
        task.resume()
        return false
    }
    if needsToPerform { delegate?.readyToPerform(request: self) }
    return self
}
```

`delegate?.readyToPerform` is `Session.perform(request:)`:

```swift
